Featured Stories

SEC Climate Change Rules

SEC Proposed Climate Disclosure Rule


The long-awaited SEC proposed climate change risk disclosure rule was published this week. The proposed SEC rule (PDF) document is long (510 pages) but the important parts are pretty much what we were expecting. The SEC guidelines draw extensively from the recommendations of the Task Force on Climate Related Disclosures (TCFD), mirroring many aspects of requirements in other jurisdictions. The major parts of the proposed rule (see page 42) require public companies to report on

  • The approach to oversight and governance of climate-related risks by the Board and executive team;
  • How climate-related risks are identified, assessed, and managed and how these processes are integrated into other risk management processes;
  • The climate related risks likely to impact financial statements, strategy, business model, and outlook in the short-, medium-, or long-term;
  • The impact of identified physcial and transition risks on financial outlook and statements;
  • Climate-related targets, goals, and transition plan(s).
  • Scope 1 (direct) and 2 (emissions from electricity, steam, heat, or cooling); and
  • Scope 3 GHG emissions and intensity (indirect upstream and downstream emissions), if material, or if the company has set a Scope 3 emissions target.

The elements most likely to attract attention are the mandatory disclosure of Scope 1 and 2 emissions, as well as the link between targets and required disclosure for Scope 3 emissions. The latter, I would expect, will be of particular interest to banks since financed emissions would generally fall into that category, as well as to oil and gas companies wherein Scope 3 emissions would include emissions associated with the transportation and eventual combustion of produced hydrocarbons.

Canada is undertaking a similar process, with draft NI 51-107 rules published last year. Given how extensively Canadian oil sands companies have relied on the talking point that most (80%+) of the wells-to-wheels emissions from their products are downstream, expect the conversation around disclosure of Scope 3 emissions to be highly contentious.

Canada’s Climate Plan

Canada’s climate plan


We should see Canada’s latest climate change plan sometime in the next couple of weeks. The government has a lot of work to do to close the gap on its Glasgow targets announced last year to reduce emissions by 40-45% below 2005 levels by 2030, and to net zero by 2050. Two interesting reports from the Net-Zero Advisory Board (NZAB) submission and the Canadian Institute for Climate Choices (CICC) clearly set out the challenge and the tools available to the federal government.

The NZAB is a government-constituted body, so it’s interesting to see what they’ve set out. Their work focuses on the big sectors (buildings, transport, and oil and gas) with stubborn emissions trajectories and lots of locked-in investment. A couple of things really stood out for me in the report: first, I was interested to see that only their oil and gas sector analysis contained an economic contribution call-out box; and I was glad to see the link between global actions and markets for Canadian oil and gas. I think we need a lot more emphasis on how much Canada is a policy-taker in terms of how global climate action affects the value of our emissions-intensive resources.

The CICC report emphasizes what they’d like to see from the government. Two parts really caught my eye: their calls for more transparent modelling and analysis including clear technology and financial assumptions, and for clear links between policies and emissions trajectories. In a nutshell, they want the government to show their work. I couldn’t agree more.

IPCC AR6 WGII

Another Climate Change Report?


It seems like we’re getting a new climate change report about once a week these days. Earlier this month, it was the report of Working Group (WG) 2 for the IPCC Sixth Assessment Report, for which the (much) shorter Summary for Policymakers is here (PDF). Working Group 2 is charged with the assessment of the impacts of climate change on our socio-economic and natural systems. Their work builds on the WG 1 report on the science of climate change, and will be followed by the WG3 report on mitigation options which is scheduled to be approved in the coming weeks.

Of the three reports in which IPCC cycle, WG2 tends to be the one on which I spend the least amount of time, as it tends to be furthest from my areas of research. That’s starting to change, especially in light of more recent cases on climate change rights (Mathur et al. v R in Ontario, Juliana v. United States, and two major cases in the Netherlands with judgements against Shell and the Dutch Government), through which the impacts of climate change have been driving policy responses in a way we haven’t seen before.

Five statements in the Summary for Policy Makers that stood out to me were:

  • “Other impacts are approaching irreversibility such as the impacts of hydrological changes resulting from the retreat of glaciers, or the changes in some mountain (medium confidence) and Arctic ecosystems driven by permafrost thaw (high confidence)” (at SPM-8);

  • “Near-term risks for biodiversity loss are (…) high to very high in Arctic sea-ice and terrestrial ecosystems (high confidence)” (at SPM-13);

  • “(In the near-term,) violent conflict and, separately, migration patterns, in the near-term will be driven by socio-economic conditions and governance more than by climate change (medium confidence)” (at SPM-13);

  • “Future exposure to climatic hazards is also increasing globally due to socio-economic development trends including migration, growing inequality and urbanization (high confidence)” (at SPM-13); and

  • “Climate change impacts and risks are becoming increasingly complex and more difficult to manage. Multiple climate hazards will occur simultaneously, and multiple climatic and non-climatic risks will interact, resulting in compounding overall risk and risks cascading across sectors and regions” (at SPM-18).
